    risks: ["**Execution Risk:** SpaceX’s ambitious timelines (e.g., Mars colonization by 2029) may face delays, impacting investor confidence.", "**Regulatory Scrutiny:** Starlink’s global expansion could face pushback from governments over spectrum allocation and national security concerns.", "**Competition:** Blue Origin, Amazon’s Project Kuiper, and China’s space program could erode SpaceX’s market share in launches and satellite internet."],
    opportunities: ["**Starlink’s Growth:** With only 3 million subscribers, Starlink has massive room to expand in emerging markets, potentially doubling revenue by 2028.", "**Starship’s Potential:** A successful Starship program could unlock new revenue streams, including lunar missions, orbital refueling, and space tourism.", "**Government Contracts:** SpaceX’s $3+ billion in annual government contracts provide a stable revenue base, with potential upside from NASA’s Artemis program and military partnerships."],
    outlook: "### What Happens Next: Key Catalysts to Watch\n\n1. **IPO Pricing (Late July):** The official pricing will set the tone for SpaceX’s public debut. A valuation above $250 billion could trigger a \"fear of missing out\" (FOMO) rally, while a pullback might spook retail investors.\n\n2. **Starship’s First Orbital Flight:** SpaceX’s next-generation rocket is critical to its Mars ambitions. A successful test flight in 2026 could send shares soaring, while a failure could raise questions about the company’s technical roadmap.\n\n3. **Starlink’s Global Expansion:** With plans to enter Africa and Southeast Asia, Starlink’s subscriber growth will be a key metric to watch. Analysts are projecting 5 million users by 2027—any shortfall could weigh on sentiment.\n\n4. **Regulatory Hurdles:** SpaceX’s FCC licenses for Starlink and its satellite spectrum holdings could face scrutiny, particularly as competitors like Amazon and Blue Origin lobby for a level playing field.\n\n5. **Musk’s Focus:** If Musk’s attention drifts to other ventures (like X or Neuralink), SpaceX’s stock could face volatility. Investors will be watching his public appearances and internal memos for clues about his priorities.",
    conclusion: "SpaceX’s IPO is more than just a stock market event—it’s a referendum on the future of space itself. For the first time, everyday investors will have the chance to own a piece of the company that’s redefining what’s possible beyond Earth’s atmosphere. But with great reward comes great risk. Between Musk’s unpredictable leadership, the technical challenges of spaceflight, and the looming threat of competition, SpaceX’s journey to the public markets is anything but a sure thing.\n\nYet, for those willing to stomach the volatility, the potential payoff is historic. If SpaceX delivers on even a fraction of its promises—whether it’s Starlink’s global dominance, Starship’s Mars missions, or the next frontier of space-based commerce—the early investors in this IPO could be looking at returns that are, quite literally, out of this world. Buckle up: the countdown to liftoff has begun.",
