    detailedAnalysis: "## Market Overview\nThe Indian IPO market has seen a significant increase in activity from SMEs, with over 20 filings in the last quarter. This trend is expected to continue, driven by regulatory changes and growing investor appetite. Recent subscription data indicates strong demand for SME IPOs, with some issues oversubscribed by over 10 times.\n## Key Developments\nSEBI\'s regulatory changes have made it easier for SMEs to access the capital markets. The regulator has simplified the listing process and reduced the costs associated with going public. This has led to a surge in SME IPO filings, with companies from a variety of sectors tapping the markets.\n## Market Impact\nThe surge in SME IPO activity is expected to have a positive impact on the broader market. It will provide investors with more opportunities to invest in growth-oriented companies and will help to deepen the capital markets. According to Rohan Shah, an analyst at a leading brokerage firm, \'SME IPOs offer a unique opportunity for investors to tap into the growth potential of small and medium-sized enterprises, which are often undervalued compared to their larger counterparts.\'\n## Expert Perspective\nAs per the views of analyst, Karan Singh, \'The key to success for SME IPOs is to identify companies with strong growth potential and attractive valuations. Investors should do their due diligence and carefully evaluate the company\'s financials and management team before investing.\'\n## Historical Context\nThe Indian IPO market has a long history of supporting SMEs. In the past, many SMEs have used the IPO route to raise funds and achieve their growth objectives. With the current trend of increasing SME IPO activity, it\'s likely that we\'ll see even more companies tapping the capital markets to raise funds.\n---\nAuthor: Shiva Sandeep\nTelegram: @its_terabyte\nPublished by PulseTrends",
